{
  "intro": {
    "title": "Verbs: Irregular Past Forms",
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Irregular verbs — three forms to learn",
        "content": "**Regular verbs** form the past with **-ed** (*work → worked*). **Irregular verbs** don't — each has its own forms: base → past simple → past participle. There is no rule to predict them: you must **learn each one**.\n- Czech speakers often default to *-ed* for unfamiliar verbs — which is always wrong for irregular ones.\n- The 50 most common cover almost everything you need at B2. Full list: **Reference → Irregular verbs**.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "Base → Past simple → Past participle",
            "headers": [
              "Base",
              "Past simple",
              "Past participle"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "go",
                "went",
                "gone"
              ],
              [
                "speak",
                "spoke",
                "spoken"
              ],
              [
                "write",
                "wrote",
                "written"
              ],
              [
                "see",
                "saw",
                "seen"
              ],
              [
                "make",
                "made",
                "made"
              ],
              [
                "take",
                "took",
                "taken"
              ],
              [
                "know",
                "knew",
                "known"
              ],
              [
                "think",
                "thought",
                "thought"
              ],
              [
                "find",
                "found",
                "found"
              ],
              [
                "give",
                "gave",
                "given"
              ]
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A1.irregular_verbs.basic"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A1"
      },
      {
        "title": "When you need each form",
        "content": "The **past simple** uses column 2; **perfect tenses** and **passives** use column 3 (past participle):",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "Which column, which structure",
            "headers": [
              "Form",
              "Used in",
              "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "**past simple** (col 2)",
                "Past simple",
                "I *saw* him yesterday."
              ],
              [
                "**past participle** (col 3)",
                "Present perfect",
                "I *have seen* him."
              ],
              [
                "**past participle** (col 3)",
                "Past perfect",
                "She *had written* it."
              ],
              [
                "**past participle** (col 3)",
                "Passive",
                "The letter *was written*."
              ],
              [
                "**past participle** (col 3)",
                "Third conditional",
                "If I *had known*, I would have told you."
              ]
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A1.irregular_verbs.basic"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A1"
      },
      {
        "title": "Common errors",
        "content": "These are the mistakes that appear most in student writing — all caused by treating an irregular verb as regular:",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "examples",
            "items": [
              {
                "bad": "He speaked to her.",
                "good": "He spoke to her.",
                "why": "speak → spoke (not speaked)"
              },
              {
                "bad": "I goed to the shop.",
                "good": "I went to the shop.",
                "why": "go → went (not goed)"
              },
              {
                "bad": "She writed a letter.",
                "good": "She wrote a letter.",
                "why": "write → wrote (not writed)"
              },
              {
                "bad": "They maked a mistake.",
                "good": "They made a mistake.",
                "why": "make → made (not maked)"
              },
              {
                "bad": "We taked the bus.",
                "good": "We took the bus.",
                "why": "take → took (not taked)"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A1.irregular_verbs.basic"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A1"
      }
    ]
  },
  "check": {
    "title": "Test your understanding",
    "questions": [
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "He _____ to me yesterday. (speak – past)",
        "options": {
          "a": "speaked",
          "b": "spoke",
          "c": "spoken",
          "d": "speak"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Speak is irregular: speak → spoke → spoken."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "I _____ to London last year. (go – past)",
        "options": {
          "a": "goed",
          "b": "went",
          "c": "gone",
          "d": "go"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Go is irregular: go → went → gone."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "She _____ a letter. (write – past)",
        "options": {
          "a": "writed",
          "b": "wrote",
          "c": "written",
          "d": "write"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Write is irregular: write → wrote → written."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "They _____ a mistake. (make – past)",
        "options": {
          "a": "maked",
          "b": "maded",
          "c": "made",
          "d": "make"
        },
        "correct_option": "c",
        "explanation": "Make is irregular: make → made → made."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "We _____ him at the party. (see – past)",
        "options": {
          "a": "seed",
          "b": "saw",
          "c": "seen",
          "d": "see"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "See is irregular: see → saw → seen."
      }
    ],
